<exercises><title> <em>Check your Understanding</em> </title>
	
	<exercise label="chkpts-motivating-example"><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>

		<introduction>
			<p>
				Complete the questions on each tab to check your understanding.
			</p>
		</introduction>

		<task label="incomplete-product-rule-in-a-de-1"><title> <em>Select-all-that-Apply</em> </title>
			<statement>

				<p>
					In this section, we found the integrating factor for the differential equation
				</p>
				<p>
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} + 2y = 5
					</me>,
				</p>
				<p>
					to be <m>e^{2x}</m>. What part of the original equation did the integrating factor depend on?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The derivative of the function on the right side of the equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor depends on the coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The derivative of the function on the left side of the equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor depends on the coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							That's correct! The integrating factor depends on the coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The constant term on the right side of the equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor depends on the coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="incomplete-product-rule-in-a-de-2"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What was the purpose of multiplying both sides of <xref ref="if-example-incomplete-eqn"/> by <m>e^{2x}</m> ?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To balance the equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Remember that the goal is to solve the equation, not to balance it.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To make the equation separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Multiplying an non-separable equation by a function will never make it separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It helps determine if the integrating factor method can be used.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Multiplying a differential equation by a function will never help determine which method can be used.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							To add the missing part of a product rule on the left-side of the equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							That's correct! Multiplying by <m>e^{2x}</m> on both sides of the equation allows us to complete the product rule on the left side.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
		
