		<task label="chkpt-completing-square-6"><title> <em>Role of the Integrating Factor</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Why is an integrating factor used in solving differential equations?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							To modify the equation so that one side becomes a perfect derivative.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor enables us to rewrite the equation in a form that allows direct integration.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To eliminate the derivative term completely.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor does not eliminate derivatives but reorganizes the equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To factor the differential equation into linear terms.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor does not factor the equation in the algebraic sense.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To make the equation homogeneous.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor does not necessarily make an equation homogeneous.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-integrating-factor-1"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following is the closest description of an integrating factor?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							A function that is multiplied onto both sides of an equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor is a function that you multiply both sides of a differential equation by.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							A particular solution to the differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is not a solution to the differential equation, but a function that helps solve it.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							An initial condition for the differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is not an initial condition, but a function that helps solve the differential equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The derivative of the dependent variable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is not the derivative of the dependent variable, but a function that helps solve the differential equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-integrating-factor-2"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which differential equation would you solve to find the integrating factor, <m>\mu</m>, for the first-order linear equation
					<me>
						y' + \frac{1}{x}y = x
					</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu' = x\mu </m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Look carefully at <xref ref="if-sov-eqn"/> to see which equation you would get.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu' = \frac{1}{x}\mu </m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct!
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu' + \frac{\mu}{x} = x </m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Look carefully at <xref ref="if-sov-eqn"/> to see which equation you would get.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu' = \frac{1}{x}y\mu </m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Look carefully at <xref ref="if-sov-eqn"/> to see which equation you would get.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-integrating-factor-3"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the integrating factor for the equation
					<me>
						y' + 3y = e^x
					</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu = e^{e^{3x}}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This is not the correct expression for the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\mu = e^{3x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor is <m>e^{3x}</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu = e^{x^2/2}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The correct integrating factor should involve the integral of the coefficient of <m>y</m>, which is <m>3</m>, not <m>x</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\mu = e^{x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This is not the correct form for the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-integrating-factor-4"><title> <em>Fill-in-the-Blank</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Rewritting the differential equation
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						2y' = 4 - 2xy
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					in the standard first-order linear form
					<me>
						y' + P(x)y = Q(x)
					</me>
					shows that
					<ul>
						<li>
							<p>
								<m>P(x) = </m> <fillin characters="10" answer="x" />
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
								<m>Q(x) = </m> <fillin characters="10" answer="2" />
							</p>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<evaluation>
				<evaluate>
					<test>
						<strcmp>\s*x\s*</strcmp>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The equation is rearranged as
								<me>
									y' + xy = 2
								</me>
								showing that <m>P(x) = x</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</test>
					<test>
						<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Double-check your algebra when rearranging the equation.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</test>
				</evaluate>
				<evaluate>
					<test>
						<strcmp>\s*2\s*</strcmp>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The equation is rearranged as
								<me>
									y' + xy = 2
								</me>
								showing that <m>Q(x) = 2</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</test>
					<test>
						<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Double-check your algebra when rearranging the equation.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</test>
				</evaluate>
			</evaluation>
		</task>

