		<task label="chkpt-integrating-factor-6"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Determine the integrating factor for the differential equation <m>\ds y'=\frac{y}{x}+2x+1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>x</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The integrating factor is <m>e^{\int-\frac{1}{x}dx}=e^{-\ln(x)}=x^{-1}</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>-x</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							TThe integrating factor is <m>e^{\int-\frac{1}{x}dx}=e^{-\ln(x)}=x^{-1}</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>x^{-1}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							TThe integrating factor is <m>e^{\int-\frac{1}{x}dx}=e^{-\ln(x)}=x^{-1}</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
			<hint>
				<p>
					Write the differential equation in the form <m>y'+P(x)y=Q(x)</m> and compute <m>e^{\int P(x)}dx</m>.
				</p>
			</hint>
		</task>

	</exercise>

	<exercise label="chkpts-motivating-example-2"><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>
	
		<task label="chkpt-motivating-example-1"><title> <em>Purpose of the Example</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the main purpose of the motivating example in this subsection?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							To illustrate how multiplying by an integrating factor can transform a differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The example demonstrates how an integrating factor helps rewrite an equation in a solvable form.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To prove that all first-order differential equations have explicit solutions.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The example does not address whether all equations have explicit solutions, only how an integrating factor can be useful.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To introduce the method of separation of variables.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method is different from separation of variables.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To show that linear equations are always homogeneous.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The example deals with a nonhomogeneous equation and focuses on transforming it.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-motivating-example-2"><title> <em>Understanding the Role of <m>\mu(x)</m></em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					In the given example, what role does <m>\mu(x) = e^{2x}</m> play?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							It is the integrating factor that allows the equation to be rewritten as a single derivative.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The function <m>e^{2x}</m> is chosen so that the left-hand side of the equation becomes a derivative.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It is a solution to the differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. <m>\mu(x)</m> is used to manipulate the equation, not to solve it directly.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It eliminates the need for integration.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. While it simplifies the equation, integration is still required to solve for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It converts the equation into a second-order differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation remains first-order throughout the process.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-motivating-example-3"><title> <em>Forming a Single Derivative</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What condition must hold for the left-hand side of the differential equation to become a single derivative?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The function <m>\mu(x)</m> must satisfy the equation <m>\frac{d\mu}{dx} = 2\mu</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! This condition ensures that multiplying by <m>\mu(x)</m> allows the product rule to be reversed.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The function <m>\mu(x)</m> must be a constant.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. If <m>\mu(x)</m> were constant, it would not allow the left-hand side to transform into a derivative.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The equation must be rewritten in homogeneous form first.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method applies to nonhomogeneous equations as well.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The right-hand side must be equal to zero.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The right-hand side does not need to be zero for the integrating factor method to work.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-motivating-example-4"><title> <em>Final Step in Solving</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					After rewriting the equation as <m>\frac{d}{dx} [e^{2x} y] = 5e^{2x}</m>, what is the next step?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Apply the product rule to expand the left-hand side.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The product rule was already reversed to reach this form; expanding it again would undo progress.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Integrate both sides to solve for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! Now that the left-hand side is a derivative, we integrate both sides to solve for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Multiply by another integrating factor.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. A second integrating factor is unnecessary.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
